Installation of VS Code:

- Visit the official Visual Studio Code website: https://code.visualstudio.com/
- Click on the "Download for Windows" button.
- Once the download is complete, run the installer.
- Follow the setup wizard instructions. Ensure to check the options to add VS Code to your PATH and to create a desktop icon.
- Click "Install" to begin the installation process.
- After the installation is complete, launch VS Code.

First-time Setup:

- Adjust settings for a preferred theme by navigating to File > Preferences > Color Theme.
- Configure the font size and family in File > Preferences > Settings, then search for "Font Size" and "Font Family".
- Install essential extensions for your development needs from the Extensions view (Ctrl+Shift+X).
- Set up code formatting rules and auto-save settings for a smoother coding experience.

User Interface Overview:

- Activity Bar: Located on the far left, it allows you to switch between different views like Explorer, Search, Source Control, and Extensions.
- Side Bar: Displays the contents of the view selected in the Activity Bar, such as the file explorer or search results.
- Editor Group: The central area where you write and edit your code. You can split this into multiple editor groups for side-by-side editing.
- Status Bar: Located at the bottom, it shows information about the current project, such as errors, warnings, and the current Git branch.

Command Palette:

- The Command Palette can be accessed by pressing Ctrl+Shift+P (or F1).
- It provides a quick way to access and execute commands.
- Common tasks include changing the color theme, opening settings, and running debugging tasks.

Extensions in VS Code:

- Extensions enhance the functionality of VS Code, such as language support, themes, and tools.
- Find extensions in the Extensions view (Ctrl+Shift+X).
- Install extensions by clicking the Install button next to the desired extension.
- Manage installed extensions from the same Extensions view.
- Essential extensions for web development include Prettier, ESLint, and Live Server.

Integrated Terminal:

- Open the integrated terminal with Ctrl+` (backtick).
- It provides a built-in terminal interface for running command-line tasks without leaving VS Code.
- Advantages include quick access, multiple terminal support, and integration with the editor.

File and Folder Management:

- Create new files or folders using the file explorer in the Side Bar or with right-click context menus.
- Open files by double-clicking them in the explorer or using Ctrl+P to quickly find and open files.
- Efficiently navigate between files using the Explorer, the Open Editors pane, or keyboard shortcuts like Ctrl+Tab.

Settings and Preferences:

- Access settings from File > Preferences > Settings or by pressing Ctrl+,
- Customize themes in the Color Theme section.
- Adjust font size by searching for "Font Size" in the settings.
- Modify keybindings in File > Preferences > Keyboard Shortcuts or by pressing Ctrl+K Ctrl+S.

Debugging in VS Code:

- Set up debugging by configuring a launch.json file in the .vscode folder.
- Start debugging by selecting the Run and Debug view from the Activity Bar or pressing F5.
- Key debugging features include breakpoints, variable inspection, and call stack navigation.

Using Source Control:

- Integrate Git by initializing a repository from the Source Control view in the Activity Bar.
- Make commits by staging changes and committing them within the Source Control view.
- Push changes to GitHub by connecting your repository and using the push command.
